CD133+ cells have a slow development rate in vitro

We investigated the growth of unsorted Colo205, CD133+ and CD133- cell fractions in basal 10% FBS in vitro culture.

While unsorted parental Colo205 cells had a population doubling time of less than 24 h (22±1.4 h), CD133+ cells had a far slower development rate (126±8.7 h) (Figure ).
('Colo205 cells', 'had', 'population time of h')

Cell cycle analyses revealed that CD133+ cells had a decreased transition rate out of the G0/G1 phase into the S phase.

In fact, less than 10% of CD133+ cells were in the S phase (6.9±0.7%), while most of them remained in the G0/G1 phase (82±2.1%).

In contrast, almost half of CD133- cells remained in the G0/G1 phase (51.2±2.3%) or had started the S phase (43.1±1.6%) (Figure ).
('half of CD133', 'remained in', 'G0/G1 phase')
('half of CD133', 'had started', 'S phase')
